The domain of this Kuni no Miyatsuko is believed to have corresponded to the later {{ill|Kikuta District|ja|菊多郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, an area centered in the southern part of what is now {{ill|Iwaki, Fukushima|ja|いわき市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Fukushima Prefecture. Later, it became part of {{ill|Takaku Province|ja|多珂国|12=draft|12=draft}}, which stretched from {{ill|Sukegawa|ja|助川|12=draft|12=draft}} to {{ill|Kumagawa, Ōkuma|ja|熊川|12=draft|12=draft}}. During the establishment of the {{ill|Ritsuryō system|ja|律令制|12=draft|12=draft}}, the region was initially incorporated into {{ill|Hitachi Province|ja|常陸国|12=draft|12=draft}}, with its northern boundary marked by "Kuma" (Kumagawa).<ref>''Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei: Fukushima no Chimei,'' p. 205.</ref> Subsequently, it was reassigned to {{ill|Mutsu Province|ja|Mutsu Province|12=draft|12=draft}}. Due to this historical trajectory, the area was regarded as the northernmost territory under the control of the {{ill|Yamato court|ja|ヤマト王権|12=draft|12=draft}} before its northern expansion and was said to host {{ill|Kikuta Seki|ja|菊多関|12=draft|12=draft}}, a precursor to the more famous {{ill|Nakoso Barrier|ja|勿来関|12=draft|12=draft}}.
